<refentry id="gluErrorString.3G">
	<refmeta id="gluErrorString.3G-meta">
		<refentrytitle>gluErrorString</refentrytitle>
		<manvolnum>3G</manvolnum>
	</refmeta>
	<refnamediv id="gluErrorString.3G-name">
		<refname>gluErrorString</refname>
		<refpurpose>produce an error string from a GL or GLU error code</refpurpose>
	</refnamediv>
	<refsynopsisdiv id="gluErrorString.3G-c_spec">
		<title>C Specification</title>
		<funcsynopsis>
			<funcprototype>
				<funcdef>const&nbsp;GLubyte&nbsp;*<function>gluErrorString</function></funcdef>
				<paramdef>GLenum&nbsp;<parameter>error</parameter></paramdef>
			</funcprototype>
		</funcsynopsis>
	</refsynopsisdiv>
	<refsect1 id="gluErrorString.3G-parameters">
		<title>Parameters</title>
		<variablelist>
			<varlistentry>
				<term><parameter>error</parameter></term>
				<listitem>
					<simpara>
						Specifies a GL or GLU error code.
					</simpara>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
		</variablelist>
	</refsect1>
	<refsect1 id="gluErrorString.3G-description">
		<title>Description</title>
		<para>
			<function>gluErrorString</function> produces an error string from a GL or GLU error code. The string is in ISO Latin 1
			format. For example, <function>gluErrorString</function>(<constant>GL_OUT_OF_MEMORY</constant>) returns the string
			<parameter>out of memory</parameter>.
		</para>
		<para>
			The standard GLU error codes are <constant>GLU_INVALID_ENUM</constant>, <constant>GLU_INVALID_VALUE</constant>, and
			<constant>GLU_OUT_OF_MEMORY</constant>. Certain other GLU functions can return specialized error codes through
			callbacks. See the <function moreinfo="refentry">glGetError</function> reference page for the list of GL error codes.
		</para>
	</refsect1>
	<refsect1 id="gluErrorString.3G-errors">
		<title>Errors</title>
		<para>
			<parameter role="bold"><constant>NULL</constant></parameter> is returned if <parameter>error</parameter> is not a valid
			GL or GLU error code.
		</para>
	</refsect1>
